Boil a #pot{} of water with a pinch of @salt{}. Rinse the @Brown Basmati Rice{175%g} in a #sieve{} under running water for ~{1%minute}. Pop the rice in the pot and boil for ~{25%minutes}, then drain and put back in the pot. Cover with a #tea towel{} and leave off the heat until the chilli is ready.

Cut the @Red Onion{1/2}(cut in half through the root, peeled and thinly sliced into half moon shapes).

Heat a splash of @olive oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-low heat. Once hot, add your onion with a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir your onion and place a #lid{} on the pan. After ~{5%minutes}, take the lid off the pan, add the @cumin{1.5%tsp} and @Tomato Puree{1%tbsp} and stir everything together.

After ~{1%minute}, add the @Chopped Tomatoes{1%400g can} and a pinch of @?sugar{} (if you have some) and turn the heat to medium.

Drain and rinse the @Mixed Beans{1/2%400g can} and add to the pan along with the @Vegetable Stock Pot{1/2}. Lastly, add the @Chipotle Paste{1/2%tbsp}. Tip: Add the chipotle paste to taste, it's hot! Simmer on low heat for ~{5-10%minutes}.

Zest and juice the @Lime{1/2} and mix a pinch of the zest and dash of the juice into the @Creme Fraiche{1}. Tip: When zesting (i.e. grating) the lime, don't go down to the white part underneath the skin as this tastes bitter.

Serve your bean chilli with your rice, a good dollop of citrus crème fraîche and a big splash of lime juice.

> We decided to use chipotle, a smoky chilli paste, produced by local farmers in Mexico, who use age-old methods to produce this rich, sweet, spicy concoction. Add bit by bit, it's hot!